  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4020110678" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4020110678" />
    <a title="Christopher Scott" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/133516020-christopher-scott"><img alt="Christopher Scott" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4020110678?book_show_action=true">May 24, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Christopher Scott" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Christopher Scott" href="/user/show/133516020-christopher-scott">Christopher Scott</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4020110678" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14773503930273215058">I&apos;m a fan of Parker, but I&apos;ve avoided his earlier books after his Scavenger&apos;s trilogy didn&apos;t grab me at all. Still, I chanced picking up this one because the price was more than fair and I was curious about his debut. There&apos;s a good story here. It&apos;s hidden a bit behind layers of technical description which, while it increases the credibility of the world, still rankles me as being excessive in its worldbuilding. The specifications behind siege engine construction and metalworking are important t</span>
  <span id="freeText14773503930273215058" style="display:none">I'm a fan of Parker, but I've avoided his earlier books after his Scavenger's trilogy didn't grab me at all. Still, I chanced picking up this one because the price was more than fair and I was curious about his debut. There's a good story here. It's hidden a bit behind layers of technical description which, while it increases the credibility of the world, still rankles me as being excessive in its worldbuilding. The specifications behind siege engine construction and metalworking are important to the plot to an extent, but it begins to get in the way of the characters, to the point that they start to seem secondary to the author's fascination with an era of engineering and forging. <br /> <br />I have some quibbles with character motivations. The leader of an order of "wizards" performs a curse at the behest of a student without thinking it through. You'd think someone in that position would know better. The student then learns to be a law fencer so they can wound a rival in revenge, but they believe killing is wrong. Yet they kill many other law fencers as they train to not kill the one they're after. The leader of a band of "savages" wants to invade a city just to kill one man face to face. The leader is a smart person, exceptionally gifted, but doesn't consider that his target would die due to some incidental conflict during the siege or skip town beforehand. It's all a bit "well, okay." You can say these lapses in judgement are due to character flaws, but at a certain point it just makes the characters look stupid and cheapens the vividly described action and well paced narrative momentum. <br /><br />The women in this book are largely written better than those I've come across in Parker's short stories or in even his most lauded books like "The Folding Knife." So that's all right then.<br /><br />There are times the reader is kept at arms length from the characters when it could be a chance to get more insight into their inner life. When the protagonist faces his former student in the court we hardly hear any of his thoughts. The tension of the scene is deflated by it becoming about a betting match between onlookers and a possible application of magic. There's a few of these types of scenes that could have been mined for emotion but end up feeling like perfunctory caps on long simmering arcs. <br /><br />For a debut this is still a great book, full of what would go on to define Parker's ouvre. If you can overlook some issues with technical descriptions and actions that get the plot moving, it's a fun read. But Parker definitely improved in his later novels, as it took me a few weeks to get around to finishing this book whereas I polished off "Sixteen Ways to Defend a Walled City" in a day. </span>
  <a data-text-id="14773503930273215058" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


