<div id="review_3548398265" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3548398265" />
    <a title="Katherine Hetzel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/24579765-katherine-hetzel"><img alt="Katherine Hetzel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1381305755p2/24579765.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3548398265?book_show_action=true">Sep 15, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Katherine Hetzel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Katherine Hetzel" href="/user/show/24579765-katherine-hetzel">Katherine Hetzel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3548398265" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10413639569573669961">Not having much luck with reading material at the mo. <br/><br/>This started off really promisingly, and I was intrigued by the characters and the world that had been created. I really enjoyed it. So, the author had a tendency to describe places in lists (loved the clerks square, where you could get stationery - as a self-confessed notebook junkie, I&apos;d have loved to have been there!) or give technical details of the building of weapons like an instruction manual, but there was still plenty of character to</span>
  <span id="freeText10413639569573669961" style="display:none">Not having much luck with reading material at the mo. <br /><br />This started off really promisingly, and I was intrigued by the characters and the world that had been created. I really enjoyed it. So, the author had a tendency to describe places in lists (loved the clerks square, where you could get stationery - as a self-confessed notebook junkie, I'd have loved to have been there!) or give technical details of the building of weapons like an instruction manual, but there was still plenty of character to take us through the building story.<br /><br />Then there's the war. And I began to flick through pages and pages of thinking about war strategy and how many folk got killed in battles and interspersed were these snippets of the characters and the underlying magic that really wasn't - maybe? - and I just got bored. <br /><br />Towards the end of the book, a new character comes in with a complete chapter of backstory/info dump that I didn't bother to read cos I couldn't see the point. It didn't move the story on, didn't explain this character's motivation for his involvement in the war... and the ending? <br /><br />By the end, I just felt confused. Probably to do with the flicking of so many pages, but the pages weren't adding anything to the story. <br /><br />Disappointed. </span>
  <a data-text-id="10413639569573669961" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


