<div id="review_1676314126" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1676314126" />
    <a title="Duncan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/41881-duncan"><img alt="Duncan" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1676314126?book_show_action=true">Oct 22, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Duncan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Duncan" href="/user/show/41881-duncan">Duncan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1676314126" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12200175242078153765">First in a trilogy, akin to the author&apos;s other series in tone and feel: cynical, plenty of black/gallows humor, and a conflict between sides that are both reasonably sympathetic. (There&apos;s one villain, but he&apos;s not a primary character.) As elsewhere, there&apos;s an intense focus on engineering and manufacturing; if you want to learn about the mechanics of medieval warfare, look no further. The premise (a prosperous city is under siege by impoverished nomadic plainspeople) doesn&apos;t seem interesting, bu</span>
  <span id="freeText12200175242078153765" style="display:none">First in a trilogy, akin to the author's other series in tone and feel: cynical, plenty of black/gallows humor, and a conflict between sides that are both reasonably sympathetic. (There's one villain, but he's not a primary character.) As elsewhere, there's an intense focus on engineering and manufacturing; if you want to learn about the mechanics of medieval warfare, look no further. The premise (a prosperous city is under siege by impoverished nomadic plainspeople) doesn't seem interesting, but it manages to come to life, and the side plots involving the commander of the city's army, a fencer who otherwise makes his living dueling to the death in the city's trial-by-combat justice system, are worth untangling. There's also an extended metaphor built around the forging of swords that doubles as commentary on how our experiences shape us. Not cheery, but compelling.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12200175242078153765" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


